solutions.content:
So reversing a part of a linked list is very similar to reversing the whole list, but we just have to handle the elements at the boundary of the reverse sublist, i.e the element before left and the element after right (let's assume that the first one is start and the second one is end).

We use the usual three pointer approach to reversing the linked list, this time just limiting the number of iterations so that we end up with c = end (i.e the element after right). 
Then we put b->next = a, but don't increment the pointers, since this is the last step of the reversing operation. Now the start of the sublist is pointed to by b and let's say we have a reference to both the start pointer (as mentioned above) and the actual starting point of the sublist (i.e left). 
Then to make the list consistent again, but with reversed order, we assign `start->next = b` and `left->next = c`. 

But now we will need to think about some edge cases.

1. What if left == 1? 
	here our start pointer will be nullptr, so we have to handle that separately and c will become the new head, so we return that.
2. What if left == right?
	here we don't have to do anything, since the length of the reversed subarray is only 1 element, so we just return the list as it was.
3. What if the list has fewer than two elements?
	then we handle that separately, checking if left == 1 and right == 2 and length == 2, then either just reversing the list, or returning the same list.

After incorporating the following checks into the code, here is the result:
```
ListNode* reverseBetween(ListNode* head, int left, int right) {
	ListNode *a = nullptr, *b = head, *c = head->next;
	if(!b || !c) return head;
	if(left == right) return head;
	for(int i = 0; i<left-1; i++) {
		a = b;
		b = c;
		c = c->next;
	}
	ListNode *start = a;
	ListNode *rev_start = b;
	a = b;
	b = c;
	c = c->next;
	for(int i = left + 1; i<right; i++) {
		b->next = a;
		a = b;
		b = c;
		c = c->next;
	}
	b->next = a;
	rev_start->next = c;
	if(left == 1) {
		return b;
	}
	start->next = b;
	return head;
}
```

**Time: O(n)**, its just a single pass of the list, (not even a full single pass)
**Space: O(1)**, just a bunch of pointers.

